@ArcJuve @mashd @rakyll To run a SQL query, the system will create a number of individual data pipeline "nodes" that recursively "pull" each other, one at a time. To pull one row, you may go all the way down the tree. This is fine for low latency queries in most settings but has poor throughput.

When I catch myself doing this, the flip is to change from "left-to-right" to a "right-to-left" approach.

In the query example, that's asking myself the dumb questions: "Do I actually know what the output should look like when this works?" And "Is that what I want?"

Think about writing a SQL query. The natural way we approach it is "left-to-right."

We start with what we have and imagine forward steps to make progress. "Maybe a group-by, and then filter on..."

If it's a straight shot, no problem. But it's often messier than that...

6. Use GraphQL when you need to build a flexible API that can evolve over time. 

With GraphQL, you can add new fields to the schema without breaking existing queries, making it easier to add new features to your API without worrying about backward compatibility.

5. Use GraphQL when you want to make it easier for front-end developers to work with your API. 

With GraphQL, front-end developers can query the API for the exact data they need, rather than having to rely on the backend to provide them with the data they need.

4. Use GraphQL when you want to simplify your API.

With REST APIs, you may end up with multiple endpoints that return similar data, but with GraphQL, you can unify those endpoints into a single query.

In general, traversal-based querying over Solid pods is highly promising. It is fast enough for Solid apps with simple queries. We're working on optimizations to improve performance for complex queries. So even if your query is too slow today, it might be faster tomorrow!

Our experiments show that for non-complex queries, this approach can start producing results in less than a second, and is fast enough for user-facing applications. For complex queries, more optimization work is needed. Read more about these findings: https://t.co/NQhV6OR4No
We have implemented such an approach in the @comunicajs query engine, which is open-source, and available on https://t.co/D6DvTWSAWh.

Such client-side query engines can make use of a "Link Traversal" approach, where links between documents are followed based on the current query that is being executed. The engine will attempt to only consider those documents that are relevant to the query.

Solid pods make use of a document-oriented interface, since a fully-fledged SPARQL endpoint could be too high-cost for hosting. Hence, smarter clients are needed to fetch documents from Solid pods, and query over them locally.
